replies.comment info:
@kayleigh mcdonald 
Hey Kayleigh, that was a great observation about what was happening then in your state! Does the time of those fires line up with what you see in these graphs? Why do you think LA's air pollution wasn't affected by the fires as badly as SF's air pollution was?
What about other cities with data depicted in this set of graphs? Are their graphs similar to what you see in California, or are there other patterns you see that make you wonder what's going on there?

@Gray Rockney 
You certainly live in an area where this question is often discussed. Near you in Los Angeles, there was an increase in air pollution in November 2018, but not nearly as much as San Francisco had at that same time. Why? 
And while you did notice New Delhi generally had really bad air pollution levels, were they equally bad all year long? What can you learn online about why New Delhi has such bad air pollution and why it might not be so bad for a short time of the year?

@Hannah L. 
I like that you didn't just notice that New Delhi is higher in air pollution than other cities, but you also saw that the pollution levels changed over the year. 
Those differences could lead to some interesting and important wonderings. When did that San Francisco spike occur, and why? Think about New Delhi's data - was it always high or are there times it's higher or lower than others? What can you find out about what caused that? And I like that you reflected back on your belief that Manhattan would be so much higher in pollution because of population and realized that wasn't the case. If population doesn't completely explain the differences in pollution, then what does?

@Kayden 

That's an interesting thought - do the cities with the greatest number of people have the highest air pollution levels? 
If you google a list of the highest ranked cities in world population, do they all have the worst air pollution as shown in these graphs? What do you see?

@Allie b 
Those are very good things to wonder! It challenges the assumption that population is the major contributing factor to pollution. Consider those places that have high pollution, or significant spikes. What can you find out about what occurred in/near those places when the spikes occurred? And what can you find out about those places that had high pollution at certain times in the year but a significant drop reported during another part of the year?
In a place like New Delhi, what can you find about a major cause of air pollution?

@Nigolas Hey Nigolas, that was a great thoughtful comment. One thing that kind of confused me is that you said that Tokyo has higher pollution than Uganda when Uganda was almost 40 million more people. Are you referring to the most populated city in Uganda? If so I don't think that would make sense because they never said anything about that. I noticed that you talked about air quality and pollution. maybe you could go more into detail about that? Maybe talk about why the air pollution is so bad? Besides that, I think you had a very thoughtful comment!
Thanks,
Andi!
